\c 3
\s1 Prayer for help
\b
\d (1) A psalm of David when he escaped from his son Absalom.\x + \xo 3:1 \xt 2Sam. 15-18\x*
\q1
\v 1 (2) Oh, Lord, so many people are against me and hostile to me!
\q1
\v 2 (3) They think of me, “Even God does not want to help or save him!”
\qr (musical interlude)\f + \fr 3:2 \fk musical interlude \ft These two words translate the Hebrew word ‘selah’. The precise meaning for ‘selah’ is not known, but most interpreters say that most likely the word is a sign for the musicians.\f*
\b
\q1
\v 3 (4) But you, O LORD, are like a shield\f + \fr 3:3 \fk shield \ft A shield is a tool of war which is usually held in the left hand to protect one's body from arrows or the swords of the enemy. David uses the figure of a shield to picture that the LORD is his Protector.\f* for me!
\q2 Only You give victory\f + \fr 3: 3 \fk victory \ft Literally, ‘(Lord) lift my head.’\f* and honor to me.
\q1
\v 4 (5) LORD, when in danger previously I have cried out to You,
\q2 and from your holy mountain\f + \fr 3: 4 \fk your holy mountain \ft pictures the House of God on the hill of Zion. (See the footnote at Ps. 2:6.) But it also pictures heaven. (Heb. 12:22)\f* You heard and answered me.
\qr (musical interlude)
\b
\q1
\v 5 (6) I am not afraid to lie down and sleep!
\q2 I feel comfortable, because you keep watch over me.
\q1
\v 6 (7) I will not be afraid
\q2 even if thousands of people surround and attack from all directions.
\b
\q1
\v 7 (8) Arise and save me, O LORD and my God!
\q2 Strike the jaw of my every enemy! Break their teeth!
\q1
\v 8 (9) Yes, LORD, only You bless and give victory to your people.
\qr (musical interlude)